    "content": "     1→# Clean Architecture - SOLID Principles Implementation\n     2→\n     3→## Overview\n     4→\n     5→This bot has been refactored to follow SOLID principles, making it maintainable, testable, and extensible.\n     6→\n     7→## SOLID Principles Applied\n     8→\n     9→### 1. **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)**\n    10→Each class has one reason to change:\n    11→- `StateService`: Only manages state persistence\n    12→- `ProjectService`: Only manages project files\n    13→- `TranscriptionService`: Only handles audio transcription\n    14→- Each command: Only handles its specific functionality\n    15→\n    16→### 2. **Open/Closed Principle (OCP)**\n    17→Open for extension, closed for modification:\n    18→- Add new commands without touching existing code\n    19→- Register commands in `main.py` only\n    20→- Bot core never needs modification\n    21→\n    22→### 3. **Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP)**\n    23→All commands are interchangeable:\n    24→- Any class implementing `Command` interface works\n    25→- `CallbackCommand` and `VoiceCommand` extend base functionality\n    26→\n    27→### 4. **Interface Segregation Principle (ISP)**\n    28→Multiple specific interfaces:\n    29→- `Command`: Basic commands\n    30→- `CallbackCommand`: Commands with button handling\n    31→- `VoiceCommand`: Commands handling voice messages\n    32→\n    33→### 5. **Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP)**\n    34→Depend on abstractions:\n    35→- Commands depend on service interfaces, not implementations\n    36→- Services are injected, not created\n    37→- Configuration is external\n    38→\n    39→## Architecture Layers\n    40→\n    41→```\n    42→┌─────────────────────────────────────┐\n    43→│           main.py                   │  Entry Point\n    44→│  (Command Registration & Config)    │\n    45→└─────────────────┬───────────────────┘\n    46→                  │\n    47→┌─────────────────▼───────────────────┐\n    48→│         core/bot.py                 │  Orchestration\n    49→│    (Thin coordination layer)        │\n    50→└──┬──────────────┬────────────────┬──┘\n    51→   │              │                │\n    52→┌──▼──────┐ ┌────▼─────┐ ┌────────▼───┐\n    53→│Commands │ │ Registry │ │  Services  │\n    54→│         │ │          │ │            │\n    55→│ start   │ │ Dynamic  │ │ State      │\n    56→│ projects│ │ Command  │ │ Project    │\n    57→│ new     │ │ Loading  │ │ Transcript │\n    58→│ status  │ │          │ │            │\n    59→│ language│ │          │ │            │\n    60→│ voice   │ │          │ │            │\n    61→└─────────┘ └──────────┘ └────────────┘\n    62→```\n    63→\n    64→## Adding a New Command\n    65→\n    66→1. Create new file: `src/commands/my_command.py`\n    67→\n    68→```python\n    69→from src.core.command import Command\n    70→\n    71→class MyCommand(Command):\n    72→    @property\n    73→    def name(self) -> str:\n    74→        return \"mycommand\"\n    75→    \n    76→    @property\n    77→    def description(self) -> str:\n    78→        return \"Does something cool\"\n    79→    \n    80→    @property\n    81→    def menu_icon(self) -> str:\n    82→        return \"🎯\"\n    83→    \n    84→    async def execute(self, update, context):\n    85→        # Your logic here\n    86→        await update.message.reply_text(\"Hello!\")\n    87→```\n    88→\n    89→2. Register in `main.py`:\n    90→\n    91→```python\n    92→from src.commands.my_command import MyCommand\n    93→\n    94→bot.register_command(MyCommand)\n    95→```\n    96→\n    97→That's it! No other changes needed.\n    98→\n    99→## Benefits\n   100→\n   101→1. **Testability**: Each component can be tested in isolation\n   102→2. **Maintainability**: Clear separation of concerns\n   103→3. **Extensibility**: Add features without breaking existing code\n   104→4. **Reusability**: Services can be used in different contexts\n   105→5. **Flexibility**: Easy to swap implementations\n   106→\n   107→## File Structure\n   108→\n   109→```\n   110→src/\n   111→├── core/           # Bot infrastructure\n   112→│   ├── command.py  # Command interfaces\n   113→│   ├── registry.py # Command management\n   114→│   └── bot.py      # Main bot orchestration\n   115→├── services/       # Business logic\n   116→│   ├── state.py    # State persistence\n   117→│   ├── project.py  # Project management\n   118→│   ├── transcription.py # Audio processing\n   119→│   └── container.py # Dependency injection\n   120→└── commands/       # Individual commands\n   121→    ├── start.py\n   122→    ├── projects.py\n   123→    ├── new_project.py\n   124→    ├── status.py\n   125→    ├── language.py\n   126→    └── voice.py\n   127→```\n   128→\n   129→## Example: Custom Analytics Command\n   130→\n   131→```python\n   132→# src/commands/analytics.py\n   133→from src.core.command import Command\n   134→\n   135→class AnalyticsCommand(Command):\n   136→    @property\n   137→    def name(self) -> str:\n   138→        return \"analytics\"\n   139→    \n   140→    @property\n   141→    def description(self) -> str:\n   142→        return \"Show usage analytics\"\n   143→    \n   144→    async def execute(self, update, context):\n   145→        # Use injected services\n   146→        projects = self.state.get_projects()\n   147→        \n   148→        total_words = 0\n   149→        for pid in projects:\n   150→            _, words = self.project_service.get_project_stats(pid)\n   151→            total_words += words\n   152→        \n   153→        await update.message.reply_text(\n   154→            f\"📊 Total projects: {len(projects)}\\n\"\n   155→            f\"📝 Total words: {total_words}\"\n   156→        )\n   157→```\n   158→\n   159→Just add to `main.py`:\n   160→```python\n   161→bot.register_command(AnalyticsCommand)\n   162→```\n   163→\n   164→## Testing\n   165→\n   166→Each component can be tested independently:\n   167→\n   168→```python\n   169→# Test service in isolation\n   170→def test_state_service():\n   171→    state = StateService(\"test_state.json\")\n   172→    state.add_project(\"001\", \"Test\")\n   173→    assert \"001\" in state.get_projects()\n   174→\n   175→# Test command with mock services\n   176→def test_status_command():\n   177→    mock_services = {\n   178→        'state': MockStateService(),\n   179→        'project': MockProjectService()\n   180→    }\n   181→    cmd = StatusCommand(mock_services)\n   182→    # Test execution\n   183→```\n   184→\n   185→## Migration from Old Code\n   186→\n   187→The old monolithic `bot.py` has been split into:\n   188→- Core infrastructure (20% of code)\n   189→- Services (30% of code)\n   190→- Commands (50% of code)\n   191→\n   192→Each piece now has a single, clear responsibility.\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it looks malicious. If it does, you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer high-level questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
